sformation of private life in rural China from 1949 to 1999. The author’s focus on the personal and the emotional sets this book apart from most studies of the Chinese family. Yan explores private lives to examine areas of family life that have been largely overlooked, such as emotion, desire, intimacy, privacy, conjugality, and individuality. He concludes that the past five decades have witnessed a dual transformation of private life: the rise of the private family, within which the private lives of individual women and men are thriving.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCommunism and familieszChinazXiajia (Heilongjiang Sheng). 0aCourtshipzChinazXiajia (Heilongjiang Sheng). 0aFamilieszChinazXiajia (Heilongjiang Sheng). 0aIntergenerational relationszChinazXiajia (Heilongjiang Sheng). 0aMarriagezChinazXiajia (Heilongjiang Sheng). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476411740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764117/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles